<TEXT>
the last rhode island beach closed by an 
oil spill in june was prepared for reopening today as state crews 
plowed oilsoaked sand 
mackerel cove in jamestown had been closed since the june 23 
accident involving the greek tanker world prodigy the tanker 
spilled about 300000 gallons of home heating oil into rhode island 
sound when it ran aground at brenton reef about a mile south of 
newport and five miles from mackerel cove 
the spill caused most rhode island beaches to be closed about a 
week but mackerel cove the hardesthit of the beaches remained 
closed because oil had soaked into the sand 
state environmental workers have been harrowing the sand to 
expose the oil to air so it can evaporate the department decided to 
bulldoze the rest of the contaminated sand instead of turning it 
because it is now a manageable amount said spokeswoman fran 
segerson 
