<TEXT>
federal housing officials are refusing to fund 
a project approved over agency officials objections by former 
secretary samuel pierce in his final days on the job a source says 
the department of housing and urban development told one america 
inc early this month it will not honor pierces decision to fund a 
project to develop a computerized listing of black entrepreneurs 
said a hud source who spoke tuesday on the condition of anonymity 
one america a marylandbased company owned by a prominent black 
republican couple had requested 421000 for the project pierce 
approved half of that jan 17 three days before he left hud after 
heading the agency for eight years 
pierces approval came despite a 61 vote against the proposal by 
a hud review committee which questioned the need for the listing 
pierce approved the funding through a technical assistance 
program over which he had authority including the right to overrule 
objections from others in the agency but his action appears at odds 
with sworn congressional testimony that he took no direct role in 
funding decisions 
pierce is scheduled to be the first witness when congressional 
hearings into influencepeddling mismanagement and possible fraud 
at hud during the reagan administration resume sept 15 
hud can halt the project despite pierces approval because the 
department never entered into a contract with one america 
since theres no contract we dont need a reason to kill it 
said the source the one america project had been put on hold by new 
hud secretary jack kemp 
attempts to reach one america officials late tuesday were 
unsuccessful the telephone at the company was not answered 
the company is owned by elaine and howard jenkins during the 
early 1980s mrs jenkins headed a group of black republicans known 
as the council of 100 and also served on a white house commission on 
small business 
jenkins is a former labor department official and was the first 
black to serve on the national labor relations board 
mrs jenkins in an interview with the associated press in july 
said she had not received any special treatment from the agency 
pierce has not returned calls seeking comment 
in a recent interview with the los angeles times pierce said 
that getting more blacks involved in hud programs was one of his 
greatest achievements at the agency but said politics played no part 
in his decisions 
a lot of blacks got business and we certainly didnt ask them 
were they republicans democrat liberal or what pierce said 
</TEXT>
