the nuclear regulatory commission is urging a 
california utility to decide soon whether to sell or dismantle its 
rancho seco nuclear power plant which voters said last june should 
close 
thomas murley director of the nrcs office of nuclear reactor 
regulation told officials of the sacramento municipal utility 
district on tuesday that uncertainty about the fate of the 
913megawatt plant was making it difficult to plan regulatory 
changes there 
the nrc must approve any transfer of the utility districts 
nuclear license to another operator but it also must approve the 
various regulatory adjustments required if the plant is 
decommissioned and dismantled 
david a boggs general manager of the utility district said 
efforts to sell the 15yearold plant probably will be abandoned if 
no agreement is reached by friday with quadrex corp of campbell 
calif 
the rancho seco station has been closed since june 7 the day 
after utility district residents voted against keeping it running 
it was the first time an operating nuclear power plant was closed by 
voter initiative 
