<TEXT>
supporters of the proposed 500 million two forks 
dam reacted with anger after a fivemonth federal review condemned 
the water project as unnecessary and environmentally damaging 
lee dehihns an environmental protection agency deputy regional 
administrator from atlanta who conducted the review announced 
tuesday that he was recommending the epa press on with efforts to 
kill the project 
denvers water board said in a statement that the decision was 
a classical example of epa bureaucratic arrogance that shows a 
full disregard for the competency and expertise of a host of 
federal state and local agencies that supported the plan 
you simply cant leave us high and dry mayor federico pena 
told reporters tuesday in reaction to dehihns announcement we 
have not been given a fair objective appraisal of this project 
the 615foothigh dam to be built 25 miles southwest of denver 
near the confluence of the south platte river and its north fork 
would flood 30 miles of scenic river valley and canyon and the town 
of deckers which has fewer than 100 residents 
the two forks dam and reservoir project would result in the 
loss of a major aquatic resource which provides irreplaceable stream 
fishery habitat and recreational resources near the denver 
metropolitan area dehihns said 
peter aa berle national audubon society president said 
dehihns deserves the heartfelt praise and gratitude of all 
concerned americans for his balanced review 
his finding that epa should proceed with a veto of this project 
is a major victory in the continuing battle to protect the world 
