officials in washington and moscow have approved a 
draft ussoviet accord on how to conduct inspections of chemical 
arms sites under a future comprehensive ban on the weapons a us 
negotiator said wednesday 
superpower negotiators in geneva meanwhile completed a proposed 
agreement on guidelines for the gradual destruction of chemical 
weapons stockpiles and installations over a 10year period us 
envoy max friedersdorf said 
both issues are major parts of longstanding 40nation 
negotiations in geneva on a global convention banning production 
stockpiling and use of chemical weapons 
friedersdorf said the us side and the soviets had not yet 
agreed on how to carry out a proposed exchange of chemical arms data 
between washington and moscow before a convention is ready 
he commented after the latest 10day round of periodic 
ussoviet expert talks on chemical weapons 
the paper approved in washington and moscow deals with procedures 
for socalled challenge inspections in the united states and the 
soviet union the two countries with the biggest chemical arsenals 
under the proposed worldwide ban challenge inspection will allow 
any country to demand a shortnotice spot probe by international 
experts of any suspected chemical weapons site 
points covered in the ussoviet accord include how to trigger 
inspections and how to deal with their findings friedersdorf said 
in an interview in the us missions daily newsletter 
