<TEXT>
it looks as though there is plenty of reason for 
optimism heading into the traditional business new year at labor 
day 1989 
the holiday was established 95 years ago as a national event 
honoring working people a special moment of respite from toil 
but over the decades it also has evolved into a time for planning 
and launching new efforts toward progress and achievement a rolling 
up of sleeves and getting back to work after the diversions of 
summer 
by most accounts the circumstances that prevail heading into the 
last four months of 1989 are about as favorable as they ever get in 
any piece of machinery as diverse and complex as the us economy 
there hasnt been a recession in nearly seven years and 
predictions of the likely time of the next downturn have lately been 
pushed back again 
revised figures issued by the government this week showed the 
economy growing at a 27 percent annual rate after adjustment for 
inflation in the second quarter of the year up from an earlier 
estimate of 17 percent 
faced with that kind of evidence fears have been fading fast 
that the federal reserves campaign to restrain inflation would 
result in any sort of severe business slump 
the inflationfighting mission appears meanwhile to have met 
with at least some shortterm success the consumer price index rose 
at a 02 percent annual rate in both june and july half the pace it 
set over the previous five months 
the producer price index of finished goods which provides a 
measure of subsurface inflationary pressures has been falling 
recently as have prices of most raw commodities 
there was no widespread drought this year as there was in 1988 
to put pressure on supplies and prices of farm products world oil 
prices havent made any menacing moves of late 
economic data released during july and august suggest that the 
economy is in a phase of disinflationary growth a combination of 
rising growth and declining inflation that typically occurs during 
periods of economic recoveries observed anthony vignola and 
stephen gallagher analysts at the investment firm kidder peabody amp 
co 
sensitive economic indicators all point to a strengthening 
economy 
along with its benefits however that prospect poses some 
problems if the economy is going to keep chugging along the 
chances would logically be reduced for a further decline in interest 
rates 
that in turn would stand as a setback for many of the numerous 
people and businesses carrying heavy debt burdens these days as 
well as for those who hoped cheaper mortgages would help them buy or 
sell a house 
a stronger economy also would imply that the federal reserve 
might go back to restrictive inflationfighting after a recent 
period of stimulating the banking system with a shot of 
antirecession medicine 
nevertheless many analysts say it is worth remembering that 
through most of the 1980s the american economy has tended to reward 
the optimists while punishing those who bet on bad times 
the economy got off to a good start for the current quarter 
stated paul boltz financial economist at the investment management 
firm t rowe price associates if july is any indication the 
likelihood of a recession looks small this year 
to be sure a boom does not look in prospect either but a soft 
landing followed by a slow takeoff should keep washington 
policymakers satisfied 
</TEXT>
