<TEXT>
trust is a basic attitude of religious people 
who also stress open acceptance of strangers these traits make them 
particularly vulnerable to swindlers 
thats the thrust of a report by the north american securities 
administrators and the council of better business bureaus 
based on a survey of cases from state securities agencies the 
report finds an alarming increase in the number of investment 
schemes peddled to religious people 
organizers of such swindles appeal to the high level of trust 
often found in religious groups and communities 
titled preying on the faithful the false prophets of the 
investment world the report says more than 15000 americans have 
lost more than 450 million in such scams in the last five years 
a growing number of investment swindlers and other sharp 
operators play on religious beliefs in order to gain the trust 
confidence and life savings of the faithful the report says 
it details major cases in 15 states where operators usually 
feigning religious motives and sometimes claiming godendowed 
business talents gained confidence of believers and their cash 
the sharp increase in such operations has resulted in a surge 
in statelevel complaints from consumers about fraud and abuse by 
selfproclaimed born again financial planners the report says 
it says they often pretend to be endorsed by local or national 
church officials or to offer divinely inspired investment advice 
about coins precious metals real estate and oil and gas well 
programs 
john c baldwin director of the utah division of securities and 
president of the north american securities administrators 
association says 
it now appears that religiously oriented swindles are one of 
todays hottest tickets for investment con artists 
the problem here is not religion but the growing number of con 
artists who are cynically exploiting religious faith in order to 
fleece unsuspecting members of the flock 
james h mcilhenny president of the council of better business 
bureaus says the religious swindler feigns interest in religious 
beliefs only insofar as they can be used to run a scam 
they will go to any lengths including the exploitation of 
churches and deeply held religious beliefs if they think it will 
work they will take their 30 pieces of silver any way they can get 
them 
baldwin describes this common mode of operation 
a con artist picks some religiously identifiable group passes 
himself off as a member in order to put victims at ease they in 
turn often drop their guard and fail to check out him or the 
socalled investment opportunity 
baldwin said the approaches usually are much the same but the 
promoted investments may be almost anything he said one outfit used 
old testament prophecy to pinpoint spots for oil wells in israel 
many con artists advertise their services in religious 
publications and on christian radio stations he says while 
others obtain religious mailing and telephone lists and use direct 
mail and coldcall tactics 
some operate on a facetoface basis renting church 
basements or making appearances before church social groups he 
says these schemes with the personal touch seem to hit the 
elderly hardest 
whenever a religiously oriented scam starts to unravel baldwin 
says the con artist often claims authorities were trying to ruin 
or embarrass the faith or church 
frequently this tactic gives the con artist the time he needs 
to move to the next congregation baldwin says this can also 
delay complaints to state agencies so long that his trail is too 
cold to follow 
baldwin emphasizes that the fiveyear estimate of more than 
15000 americans losing more than 450 million includes only 
largescale religious scams each with losses exceeding 500000 
and not smaller swindles 
offering tips for avoiding such scams the report lists various 
danger signs including 
investments that seem closely tied to a particular religious 
belief 
an investment promoter who tries to capitalize on status or 
influence in a particular religious group 
a new member turns up with a sure fire investment scheme 
any investments promoted by fellow church members since the 
most persuasive hook of con artists is to get testimony of 
your friends and fellow believers 
sometimes swindlers plead for christian forgiveness or warn 
of harm to the faith if the scam is exposed the report says adding 
dont listen to these selfserving appeals or be talked into 
letting an investment crook off the hook he or she will just take 
the opportunity to move on to greener pastures and new victims 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

