seeking to buy ual to spell out the expectations of uniteds 
mechanics and technical workers should they support his bid 
and uniteds flight attendants have urged uals board to resume 
contract negotiations saying that in the event of an auction the 
airline will be more valuable with settled contracts the talks 
recently broke down after about two years 
davis has given uals board until thursday to respond to his 
275ashare offer which he raised from 240 a share on aug 16 
the new york meeting of leaders of the united chapter of the air 
line pilots association was believed to be focused on the 
maneuvering for control of the nations secondlargest airline said 
james hanson a spokesman for the united pilots in chicago 
theyre dealing with all this takeover stuff and its impact on 
the pilots but i couldnt give you any specifics on what is going to 
be discussed he said 
the new york times reported tuesday that representatives of the 
pilots union and chicagobased ual had spent the weekend putting 
together a package to present to the united chapters 27member 
master executive council 
pilot leaders and ual officials reportedly have met several times 
in the three weeks since davis initial offer was revealed to 
discuss an employeemanagement buyout or a recapitalization that 
would put enough stock in an employee stock ownership plan to fend 
off a hostile takeover attempt 
united pilots have been seeking an ownership role in the airline 
since 1987 industry analysts have speculated that management might 
invite employees to join in a buyout of ual in exchange for contract 
concessions that could end longrunning labor disputes between the 
company and its pilots and flight attendants unions 
without the support of the flight attendants and machinists the 
pilots might have to assume a heavier financial burden in the form 
of deeper contract concessions 
alpa represents most of uniteds 6300 pilots the association of 
flight attendants which represents another 12700 united workers 
has urged the ual board to proceed with caution 
in a letter to the board last week the attendants called for a 
resumption of contract talks 
the united chapter of the international association of machinists 
and aerospace workers which represents 25000 of uals 70000 
employees said last friday in a letter to the ual board that they 
would vigorously oppose any buyout or restructuring of the 
company 
