copper futures prices rebounded wednesday on news of a strike 
vote by workers at a chilean copper corp mine but gains were 
tempered by reports that labor troubles elsewhere may be easing 
on other futures markets frozen pork belly prices remained 
strong cattle and hog prices were mostly lower wheat futures fell 
corn and soybeans were mixed precious metals declined and oil 
futures rallied 
in trading at the new york commodity exchange copper settled 1 
cent to 185 cents higher with the contract for delivery in 
september at 129 a pound 
the markets strong tone came from reports that workers at 
chilean coppers el salvador mine voted to strike on sept 1 said 
stephen platt a metals analyst with dean witter reynolds inc in 
chicago 
although labor and management were continuing to talk after 
tuesdays vote copper prices closed firm over that strike 
uncertainty platt said 
still the market failed to regain the strength it had shown 
before tuesdays collapse when prices settled at least 7 cents 
lower the settlement price wednesday of the september contract was 
just a penny higher than tuesdays 
weakness stems from a feeling among traders that settlements may 
be near in walkouts at highland valley copper cos highland valley 
mine in british columbia and in peru 
most people are feeling that the supply thinness emanating from 
the special situations is easing platt said 
gold and silver prices declined in mostly featureless trading at 
the new york commodity exchange 
pressure on both metals came from the strength of the dollar 
analysts said gold selling also was encouraged by concerns that 
tuesdays gains were somewhat overdone platt said 
gold prices settled 150 to 180 lower with the contract for 
delivery in september at 36180 a troy ounce silver settled 8 
cent to 1 cent lower with the september contract at 5085 a troy 
ounce 
pork belly prices held strong in trading at the chicago 
mercantile exchange where cattle and hog futures were mostly lower 
the bellies strength was tied to rumors of possible export sales 
of us pork to poland while gains were tempered by a lack of 
strong market fundamentals 
supplies remain abundant and theres been no sign that lobbying 
by pork producers has persuaded the bush administration to include 
pork in in whatever charity package were going to be sending to 
poland said phillip stanley a livestock consultant in chicago 
with dec futures inc 
we bought the rumor we havent necessarily sold the fact 
he said the market wants to see something in writing the ball 
definitely rests in the adminstrations hands 
live cattle settled 20 cent to 105 cents lower with the 
contract for delivery in september at 7250 cents a pound feeder 
cattle were 37 cent lower to 05 cent higher with september at 
8250 cents a pound live hogs were 90 cent lower to 15 cent 
higher with october at 4077 cents a pound and pork bellies 
settled 05 cent lower to 65 cent higher with february at 4317 
cents a pound 
wheat futures dipped while corn and soybeans were mixed in 
trading at the chicago board of trade 
weather concerns kept a lid on prices as the national weather 
services 30day forecast does not include a chance for an early 
frost and calls instead for nrmal rain and temperatures in the 
midwest 
in addition more rain is expected to move into the midwest by 
the end of the week adding further downward pressure to prices 
analysts said 
wheat settled 2 cents lower to 1 cents higher with the 
contract for delivery in september at 385 a bushel corn was 
cent lower to cent higher with september at 231 a bushel oats 
were 2 cents to 2 cents lower with september at 132 a bushel 
and soybeans settled 3 cents lower to 1 cent higher with september 
at 579 a bushel 
oil and gasoline futures climbed at the new york mercantile 
exchange 
crude oil settled 19 cents to 31 cents higher with the contract 
for delivery in october up 19 cents at 1883 a barrel heating oil 
was 81 cent to 103 cents higher with september at 5311 cents a 
gallon and unleaded gasoline settled 39 cent to 62 cents a 
gallon with september at 55 cents a gallon 
