<TEXT>
the philadelphia stock exchange facing a ban 
on stock basket trading announced wednesday it filed documents 
to clarify that the investments are securities not futures 
contracts 
the amended proposal filed with the securities and exchange 
commission was in response to an aug 18 decision by the 7th us 
circuit court of appeals in chicago which halted trading in stock 
baskets investments based on the value of broad market indexes 
the court said the sec erred last may in approving stock baskets 
also known as cash index participation shares because they do not 
fall under the secs jurisdiction the court classified the 
investments not as stocks but as futures contracts which fall under 
the jurisdiction of the commodity futures trading commission 
in addition to the philadelphia exchange the american stock 
exchange and the chicago board of options exchange have traded stock 
baskets for several months 
according to a news release from the philadelphia exchange the 
new filing contains proposals that will allow investors who buy or 
sell stock baskets to sell their shares at any time without any 
penalty 
previously investors were charged a penalty unless the sales 
came at the end of a quarter 
also under the new filing those investors selling the 
instruments will receive a price that reflects the value of the 
underlying stocks at the opening of the market that day rather than 
at the previous days close 
these changes are in line with the ruling of the 7th circuit 
court and should remove once and for all the obstacles that stand 
before us said nicholas a giordano the exchanges president 
the philadelphia exchange first sought sec approval for stock 
baskets in march 1988 
baskets are priced to reflect changes in indexes such as the 
standard amp poors 500stock index and the dow jones average of 30 
industrial stocks investors receive quarterly cash payments equal 
to a proportionate share of any regular cash dividends declared on 
the stocks in the index 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

