<TEXT>
oilman and corporate raider t boone pickens said 
wednesday he will not run for governor in 1990 but left open his 
options for 1994 
the 61yearold pickens said the crush of his business would not 
allow him to commit 100 percent of his time to the needs of the 
state 
its not the time he told about 500 people at a dallas 
rotary luncheon ending weeks of speculation 
pickens said he had prepared two versions of his speech one 
announcing his candidacy and the one he delivered he and his wife 
beatrice reached their decision late tuesday at their hotel room in 
dallas pickens said and were still discussing it wednesday morning 
pickens did not rule out a run in 1994 thats an option he 
said 
pickens would not endorse any of the republican candidates who 
would have been his rivals in the gop primary 
his decision not to run pickens said was based on his 
involvement in his mesa limited partnership koito manufacturing and 
his united shareholders association 
mesa an oil and gas firm lost 134 million in the second 
quarter and will likely post a loss in the third quarter pickens 
said refusing to speculate on how large the loss might be 
he blamed the losses on declining natural gas prices pickens 
once feared as a corporate raider and who made a 518 million pretax 
profit in a 1983 attempted takeover of gulf oil corp said it was 
the first loss for the company in 16 years 
